               <history>
                  <origin>Completed in the <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace>, undated, but probably <date cert="high"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1750" notAfter="1809">late 18th
                        century</date>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Formerly in the collection of bookseller, poet, orientalist, artist
                        and dentist <persName role="fmo" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/55689478/"
                           key="person_55689478">Charles Fox (1749–1809)</persName>. Born in
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011359"
                           >Falmouth</placeName>, he owned a bookshop until it burned, after which
                        he travelled to the Baltic then returned and settled in <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011198">Bristol</placeName> where
                        he practiced dentistry, but then ultimately relocated to <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011197">Bath</placeName>. Fox's
                        friend and student of Persian, the Methodist theologian Rev. <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/120696480"
                           key="person_120696480">Adam Clarke (ca. 1762–1832)</persName> describes
                        the volume in his <title>Biographical Miscellany</title> published in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1806">1806</date>:</p>
                     <p><quote xml:lang="en"><hi rend="italic">Girbah Moosh</hi>, or the wars of the
                           king Cat with the community of Rats. A satirical poem on some Eastern
                           King. I have never seen but ene[sic] copy of this work: it is a small
                           folio, ornamented with curious paintings, and makes a part of the
                           valuable collection of Oriental MSS. in the possession of C. Fox, Esq. of
                           Bristol.</quote>. After Fox's death, his widow gave the volume with other
                        manuscripts and drawings to Clarke (see Etheridge and
                     Smith).</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p> After Clarke's death, his son <persName role="fmo"
                           key="person_79253656" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/79253656/">Jospeh
                           Butterworth Bulmer Clarke (d. 1855)</persName> inherited the volume and
                        describes it in his catalogue, no. 84, published in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1835">1835</date>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>The next year, Clarke's son auctioned his father's collection
                        through the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                           >London</placeName> firm of <orgName role="auc"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/133731879" key="person_133731879">Sotheby &amp;
                           Son</orgName> on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1836-06-20">20 Jun.
                           1836</date>, where bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/34804600" key="person_34804600">William
                           Straker</persName> purchased the manuscript for £8-5s.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Straker then probably sold the volume to scholar <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                           key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland
                     (1803–1865)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Bland's death, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781">London</placeName>
                        bookseller <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379"
                           role="dnr">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                           key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                           (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379" role="dnr"
                           >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/" role="rps">John Rylands
                           Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
